00015 uint64_t
00016 RegisterDictionary::hash(const RegisterDescriptor &d)
00017 {
00018     uint64_t h = d.get_major() << 24;
00019     h ^= d.get_minor() << 16;
00020     h ^= d.get_offset() << 8;
00021     h ^= d.get_nbits();

00025 void
00026 RegisterDictionary::insert(const std::string &name, const RegisterDescriptor &rdesc) {
00027     /* Erase the name from the reverse lookup map, indexed by the old descriptor. */
00028     Entries::iterator fi = forward.find(name);
00029     if (fi!=forward.end()) {
00030         Reverse::iterator ri = reverse.find(hash(fi->second));
00031         ROSE_ASSERT(ri!=reverse.end());
00032         std::vector<std::string>::iterator vi=std::find(ri->second.begin(), ri->second.end(), name);
00033         ROSE_ASSERT(vi!=ri->second.end());
00034         ri->second.erase(vi);
00035     }
00036 
00037     /* Insert or replace old descriptor with a new one and insert reverse lookup info. */
00038     forward[name] = rdesc;
00039     reverse[hash(rdesc)].push_back(name);
00040 }

00068 const std::string &
00069 RegisterDictionary::lookup(const RegisterDescriptor &rdesc) const {
00070     Reverse::const_iterator ri = reverse.find(hash(rdesc));
00071     if (ri!=reverse.end()) {
00072         for (size_t i=ri->second.size(); i>0; --i) {
00073             const std::string &name = ri->second[i-1];
00074             Entries::const_iterator fi = forward.find(name);
00075             ROSE_ASSERT(fi!=forward.end());
00076             if (fi->second.equal(rdesc))
00077                 return name;
00078         }
00079     }
00080     
00081     static const std::string empty;
00082     return empty;
00083 }

00314

00323          * set to all ones to indicate a NaN value. */

00325         regs->insert("mm1", x86_regclass_mm, 1, 0, 64);
00326         regs->insert("mm2", x86_regclass_mm, 2, 0, 64);

00330         regs->insert("mm6", x86_regclass_mm, 6, 0, 64);
00331         regs->insert("mm7", x86_regclass_mm, 7, 0, 64);
00332     }
00333     return regs;

00457         regs->insert("cpsr_z", arm_regclass_psr, arm_psr_current, 30, 1);    /* zero flag (0=>not zero; 1=>zero) */
00458         regs->insert("cpsr_n", arm_regclass_psr, arm_psr_current, 31, 1);    /* sign flag (0=>not signed; 1=>signed) */
00459 
00460         /* The six spsr registers (at most one available depending on the operating mode), have the same bit fields as the cpsr
00461          * register. When an exception occurs, the current status (in cpsr) is copied to one of the spsr registers. */
00462         regs->insert("spsr_m", arm_regclass_psr, arm_psr_saved,  0, 5);    /* Mode bits indicating saved operating mode */
00463         regs->insert("spsr_t", arm_regclass_psr, arm_psr_saved,  5, 1);    /* State bit (0=>ARM; 1=>THUMB) */

00465         regs->insert("spsr_i", arm_regclass_psr, arm_psr_saved,  7, 1);    /* IRQ disable (0=>enable; 1=>disable) */

00476 const RegisterDictionary *
00477 RegisterDictionary::dictionary_powerpc()
00478 {
00479     static RegisterDictionary *regs = NULL;
00480     if (!regs) {
00481         regs = new RegisterDictionary("powerpc");
00482 
00483         /**********************************************************************************************************************
00484          * General purpose and floating point registers
00485          **********************************************************************************************************************/
00486         for (unsigned i=0; i<32; i++) {
00487             regs->insert("r"+StringUtility::numberToString(i), powerpc_regclass_gpr, i, 0, 32);
00488             regs->insert("f"+StringUtility::numberToString(i), powerpc_regclass_fpr, i, 0, 64);
00489         }
00490 
00491         /**********************************************************************************************************************
00492          * State, status, condition, control registers
00493          **********************************************************************************************************************/
00494 
00495         /* Machine state register */
00496         regs->insert("msr", powerpc_regclass_msr, 0, 0, 32);
00497 
00498         /* Floating point status and control register */
00499         regs->insert("fpscr", powerpc_regclass_fpscr, 0, 0, 32);
00500 
00501         /* Condition Register. This register is grouped into eight fields, where each field is 4 bits. Many PowerPC
00502          * instructions define bit 31 of the instruction encoding as the Rc bit, and some instructions imply an Rc value equal
00503          * to 1. When Rc is equal to 1 for integer operations, the CR field 0 is set to reflect the result of the instruction's
00504          * operation: Equal (EQ), Greater Than (GT), Less Than (LT), and Summary Overflow (SO). When Rc is equal to 1 for
00505          * floating-point operations, the CR field 1 is set to reflect the state of the exception status bits in the FPSCR: FX,
00506          * FEX, VX, and OX. Any CR field can be the target of an integer or floating-point comparison instruction. The CR field
00507          * 0 is also set to reflect the result of a conditional store instruction (stwcx or stdcx). There is also a set of
00508          * instructions that can manipulate a specific CR bit, a specific CR field, or the entire CR, usually to combine
00509          * several conditions into a single bit for testing. */
00510         regs->insert("cr", powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, 0, 32);
00511         for (unsigned i=0; i<32; i++) {
00512             switch (i%4) {
00513                 case 0:
00514                     regs->insert("cr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i/4), powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, i, 4);
00515                     regs->insert("cr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i/4)+"*4+lt", powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, i, 1);
00516                     break;
00517                 case 1:
00518                     regs->insert("cr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i/4)+"*4+gt", powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, i, 1);
00519                     break;
00520                 case 2:
00521                     regs->insert("cr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i/4)+"*4+eq", powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, i, 1);
00522                     break;
00523                 case 3:
00524                     regs->insert("cr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i/4)+"*4+so", powerpc_regclass_cr, 0, i, 1);
00525                     break;
00526             }
00527         }
00528 
00529         /* The processor version register is a 32-bit read-only register that identifies the version and revision level of the
00530          * processor. Processor versions are assigned by the PowerPC architecture process. Revision levels are implementation
00531          * defined. Access to the register is privileged, so that an application program can determine the processor version
00532          * only with the help of an operating system function. */
00533         regs->insert("pvr", powerpc_regclass_pvr, 0, 0, 32);
00534 
00535         /**********************************************************************************************************************
00536          * The instruction address register is a pseudo register. It is not directly available to the user other than through a
00537          * "branch and link" instruction. It is primarily used by debuggers to show the next instruction to be executed.
00538          **********************************************************************************************************************/
00539         regs->insert("iar", powerpc_regclass_iar, 0, 0, 32);
00540 
00541         /**********************************************************************************************************************
00542          * Special purpose registers. There are 1024 of these, some of which have special names.  We name all 1024 consistently
00543          * and create aliases for the special ones. This allows the disassembler to look them up generically.  Because the
00544          * special names appear after the generic names, a reverse lookup will return the special name.
00545          **********************************************************************************************************************/
00546         /* Generic names for them all */
00547         for (unsigned i=0; i<1024; i++)
00548             regs->insert("spr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i), powerpc_regclass_spr, i, 0, 32);
00549 
00550         /* The link register contains the address to return to at the end of a function call.  Each branch instruction encoding
00551          * has an LK bit. If the LK bit is 1, the branch instruction moves the program counter to the link register. Also, the
00552          * conditional branch instruction BCLR branches to the value in the link register. */
00553         regs->insert("lr", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_lr, 0, 32);
00554 
00555         /* The fixed-point exception register contains carry and overflow information from integer arithmetic operations. It
00556          * also contains carry input to certain integer arithmetic operations and the number of bytes to transfer during load
00557          * and store string instructions, lswx and stswx. */
00558         regs->insert("xer", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_xer, 0, 32);
00559 
00560         /* The count register contains a loop counter that is decremented on certain branch operations. Also, the conditional
00561          * branch instruction bcctr branches to the value in the CTR. */
00562         regs->insert("ctr", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_ctr, 0, 32);
00563 
00564         /* Other special purpose registers. */
00565         regs->insert("dsisr", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_dsisr, 0, 32);
00566         regs->insert("dar", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_dar, 0, 32);
00567         regs->insert("dec", powerpc_regclass_spr, powerpc_spr_dec, 0, 32);
00568 
00569         /**********************************************************************************************************************
00570          * Time base registers. There are 1024 of these, some of which have special names. We name all 1024 consistently and
00571          * create aliases for the special ones. This allows the disassembler to look them up generically.  Because the special
00572          * names appear after the generic names, a reverse lookup will return the special name.
00573          **********************************************************************************************************************/
00574         for (unsigned i=0; i<1024; i++)
00575             regs->insert("tbr"+StringUtility::numberToString(i), powerpc_regclass_tbr, i, 0, 32);
00576 
00577         regs->insert("tbl", powerpc_regclass_tbr, powerpc_tbr_tbl, 0, 32);      /* time base lower */
00578         regs->insert("tbu", powerpc_regclass_tbr, powerpc_tbr_tbu, 0, 32);      /* time base upper */
00579     }
00580     return regs;
00581 }
